accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Open for researchd. Brittle or damaged items are available at the discretion of RAC. arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: This collection is arranged in four series:

bioghist.head: Biographical/Historical note
bioghist.p: The International Education Board was incorporated January 12, 1923, in the state of Virginia. Its purpose was to promote education, institutional or otherwise, throughout the world and as such was a complement to the General Education Board which functioned in the United States. Wickliffe Rose resigned from the International Health Board in 1923 to become director of both boards. At his retirement in 1928, the International Education Board discontinued its active program.

The International Education Board promoted the advancement of education through grants to universities and through a multitude of fellowships to individuals. It sponsored the strengthening of disciplines with such grants as those to develop Mount Palomar and traveling professorships and fellowships. While the main fields of the board were the physical and natural sciences and agriculture, some appropriations were made in the humanities and social sciences as to the American Academy in Rome, the Oriental Institute in Chicago and the New York State Colonization Society for the Booker Washington Agricultural and Industrial Institute of Liberia.
The Board terminated its activities on December 31, 1938.
A history, "Education on an International Scale," was written by George Gray.
The International Education Board records cover the period from 1923 to 1960.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Important subjects in this collection are astronomy, agriculture, rural clubs, physics, chemistry, dairying, biology, marine biology, mathematics, Mount Palomar, Oriental Institute, veterinary medicine, home economics, scientific publications, agricultural education, geology, forestry, Negro education, international education, and the National Research Council.

Among the correspondents are R. A. Millikan, W. W. Bierly, W. S. Richardson, Anson Phelps Stokes, Jackson Davis, W. H. Shepardson, Wickliffe Rose, H. L. Russell, George Foster Peabody, Ray Lyman Wilbur, Frank R. Lillie, Oswald Veblen, Augustus Trowbridge, Abraham Flexner, Simon Flexner, Louise Stanley, H. C. Taylor, Frants P. Lund, Vernon Kellog, W. E. Tisdale, C. B. Hutchison, A. R. Mann, Arthur A. Noyes, A. O. Leuschner, E. G. Nourse, George Asher Hobson, S. T. Dana, Martha van Rensselaer, Florence M. Read, Charles T. Loram, Harlow Shapley, Frank Schlesinger, Charles Breasted, James Breasted, John A. Wilson, Paul Monroe, Thomas H. Morgan, Frank Heath, Albert Einstein, Ernest Rutherford, Nils Bohr, Enrico Fermi, H. von Euler, Marie Curie, and Emil Godlewski.

processinfo.head: Processing Information note
processinfo.p: Processing was completed as of August 11, 1970. Processing Level 3: Standard Processing. All material is available in acid free manuscript boxes and folders.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition note
acqinfo.p: The records of the International Education Board were deposited with the General Education Board in 1938.

scopecontent.p: Materials in this series include correspondence, memoranda, charts, clippings, drawings, reports, surveys, manuscripts and reprints.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: This series is arranged into 4 subseries as follows:

odd.head: International Education Board Appropriations Index
odd.p: A card index to the International Education Board records, Series 1: Appropriations is available for researcher use. The IEB Appropriations Index provides indexing to Subseries 1.1 through 1.4 in a single series of index cards, arranged A-Z.

'Subseries 1.1: Numerical' files are indicated by file-numbers ranging from 22 to 4003. For example, file-number "22' indicates the IEB appropriations file "John D. Rockefeller 3rd, 1934-1937" in box 1, folder 1. This collection guide provides file-numbers in the "File Plan Note" for each file.

'Subseries 1.2: Foreign Countries' files are indicated by a county name, followed by a sequential file number. For example, "Canada 3" indicates the IEB appropriations file "Canada 3 - Ontario Agricultural College, 1923" in box 26, folder 377.
'Subseries 1.3: Fellowships in Science' files are indicated by the classification "A" in the upper right corner of the index card.
'Subseries 1.4: Fellowships in Agriculture' files are indicated by the classification "B" in the upper right corner of the index card.
The IEB Appropriations Index is located in drawers 31-32 of the 72 drawer cabinet next to the RAC's reading room.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: In addition to information on appropriations, this series also contains administrative folders on staff members and general information on particular organizations in the natural sciences and agriculture.

arrangement.head: Arrangement note
arrangement.p: As is indicated by the Title, this subseries is arranged numerically. Each file has been assigned an index number, provided in this guide as a File Plan note.

did.unittitle: Survey of Far East - Harry Luman Russell

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Includes material related to Harry Luman Russell's trip through Asia and survey of the scientific and agricultural education needs in Japan, China, the Philippines, Siam, Java, Australia, and New Zealand. Includes "Synopsis of Course of Procedure to Follow in Education Survey of Far East" by Russell.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Harry Luman Russell (1866-1954) was an American bacteriologist and educator. Russell was graduated from the University of Wisconsin in 1884, received an M.S. from Wisconsin in 1890, and a Ph.D. from Johns Hopkins in 1892. Russell then became a Professor at the University of Wisconsin. In 1903 Russell was made Director of the Wisconsin State Hygienic Laboratory, and became Dean of the University of Wisconsin's College of Agriculture in 1907. Russell was also a charter member of the American Society for Microbiology, and was named President in 1908. In 1925 Russell was commissioned by the International Education Board (IEB) to travel through Asia, and survey the scientific and agricultural education needs in Japan, China, the Philippines, Siam, Java, Australia, and New Zealand.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The International Education Board was incorporated January 12, 1923, in the state of Virginia. Its purpose was to promote education, institutional or otherwise, throughout the world and as such was a complement to the General Education Board which functioned in the United States. Wickliffe Rose resigned from the International Health Board in 1923 to become director of both boards. At his retirement in 1928, the International Education Board discontinued its active program.

The International Education Board promoted the advancement of education through grants to universities and through a multitude of fellowships to individuals. It sponsored the strengthening of disciplines with such grants as those to develop Mount Palomar and traveling professorships and fellowships. While the main fields of the board were the physical and natural sciences and agriculture, some appropriations were made in the humanities and social sciences as to the American Academy in Rome, the Oriental Institute in Chicago and the New York State Colonization Society for the Booker Washington Agricultural and Industrial Institute of Liberia.
The Board terminated its activities on December 31, 1938.
